WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.189 --> 00:00:03.630
&gt;&gt; Male Presenter: Good afternoon ladies and
gentlemen.

00:00:03.630 --> 00:00:05.310
Hopefully everyone on VC can hear us.

00:00:05.310 --> 00:00:10.440
Uh, my name is Dontae Rayford, and on behalf
of Authors@Google and the Black Googler Network,

00:00:10.440 --> 00:00:14.889
I’m really excited to announce today’s
speaker, Mr. Baratunde Thurston.

00:00:14.889 --> 00:00:20.460
Um, Baratunde is described as a politically
active, tech loving comedian.

00:00:20.460 --> 00:00:24.880
He currently serves as the Director of Digital
for The Onion, and he’s also the co-founder

00:00:24.880 --> 00:00:26.830
of Jack and Jill Politics.

00:00:26.830 --> 00:00:32.239
He is a D.C. native, graduated from Harvard
University, and he currently lives in Brooklyn,

00:00:32.239 --> 00:00:33.390
New York.

00:00:33.390 --> 00:00:38.260
His first book, How to Be Black, which he’s
here to speak to us about today, was published

00:00:38.260 --> 00:00:42.339
this month, black history month, February
2012 by Harper Collins.

00:00:42.339 --> 00:00:45.350
Without further ado, I’d like to welcome
Mr. Baratunde Thurston.

00:00:45.350 --> 00:00:46.350
[Applause]

00:00:46.350 --> 00:00:50.200
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: What’s up everybody?

00:00:50.200 --> 00:00:54.730
[Audience murmurs]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: Happy black history

00:00:54.730 --> 00:00:55.730
month.

00:00:55.730 --> 00:00:56.940
Give yourselves a round of applause for black
people.

00:00:56.940 --> 00:01:00.750
[Applause]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: All people, but especially,

00:01:00.750 --> 00:01:01.839
especially us.

00:01:01.839 --> 00:01:05.110
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: It’s, uh, it’s

00:01:05.110 --> 00:01:08.330
good to be here at the Googleplex.

00:01:08.330 --> 00:01:13.270
I saw some strange, you have like a, sort
of E.T. type pod going on.

00:01:13.270 --> 00:01:16.050
There’s like these zipped up tents that
people are workin' in.

00:01:16.050 --> 00:01:18.590
And then I met someone, she said she worked
in People Operations.

00:01:18.590 --> 00:01:20.330
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: And I was, are you

00:01:20.330 --> 00:01:22.160
experimenting on the human genome?

00:01:22.160 --> 00:01:24.080
Like, it’s just a little disconcerting.

00:01:24.080 --> 00:01:29.660
Basically, for those of you watching on video,
this may be my last appearance in public.

00:01:29.660 --> 00:01:32.340
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: Tell my family I love

00:01:32.340 --> 00:01:33.990
them, very much.

00:01:33.990 --> 00:01:40.480
Uh, I wanna talk about, uh, “blackness”,
the book, my life, a little bit of tech stuff

00:01:40.480 --> 00:01:42.210
and wrap it all into one.

00:01:42.210 --> 00:01:48.010
Why don’t we just get started with this,
uh, first a little bit more background of,

00:01:48.010 --> 00:01:49.010
uh, who I am.

00:01:49.010 --> 00:01:50.090
I’m a stand-up comic.

00:01:50.090 --> 00:01:52.610
I’ve been doing comedy for about ten years.

00:01:52.610 --> 00:01:57.409
I started off in Boston and moved to New York
four and a half, five years ago.

00:01:57.409 --> 00:02:00.430
I co-founded this blog, Jack and Jill Politics.

00:02:00.430 --> 00:02:03.619
It started in the summer of 2006 with Cheryl
Contee.

00:02:03.619 --> 00:02:07.390
And it’s a blog about U.S. politics, usually
from a black perspective.

00:02:07.390 --> 00:02:11.310
The watermelon is our logo, and that symbolizes
intelligence.

00:02:11.310 --> 00:02:14.761
Most smart people love watermelon and that’s
really all that there is to it.

00:02:14.761 --> 00:02:15.770
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: If you see something

00:02:15.770 --> 00:02:20.200
else you should get yourself checked out cause
you have issues.

00:02:20.200 --> 00:02:22.580
You know, watermelon is just wonderful.

00:02:22.580 --> 00:02:28.440
I hosted a TV show on Discovery Science channel
a few years ago called Popular Science's Future

00:02:28.440 --> 00:02:31.360
Of, and it was really cool for me to be able
to do this show.

00:02:31.360 --> 00:02:36.810
We traveled around the world looking at questions
about how we might live in ten to twenty years.

00:02:36.810 --> 00:02:42.380
The future of sex, future of play, future
of habitat and what I learned most importantly

00:02:42.380 --> 00:02:46.520
is that in the future, all black people will
be required to wear wet suites.

00:02:46.520 --> 00:02:50.220
So make sure you get yours, uh, because supplies
are running out.

00:02:50.220 --> 00:02:51.820
Global warming is coming.

00:02:51.820 --> 00:02:55.959
I now, uh, work as Director of Digital for
The Onion, America’s finest news source.

00:02:55.959 --> 00:02:59.090
I’ve been there for over four years and
I’ve had a great time.

00:02:59.090 --> 00:03:05.450
My chief contribution, however, is to be every
black person in all the images that The Onion

00:03:05.450 --> 00:03:06.810
uses in this journalism.

00:03:06.810 --> 00:03:12.569
[laughter] In this case, I played Obama’s
hillbilly half cousin, Cooter Obama, and threaten

00:03:12.569 --> 00:03:13.920
to derail his campaign.

00:03:13.920 --> 00:03:20.550
Obviously, Cooter did not succeed, and others
are still attempting to derail the president.

00:03:20.550 --> 00:03:24.690
Um, and I, this is a very important aspect
of my life.

00:03:24.690 --> 00:03:29.450
I do a lot of public service work, a lot of
community service and sort of volunteer efforts.

00:03:29.450 --> 00:03:32.920
And, the chief thing that I do is I live hate
tweet the Twilight movies.

00:03:32.920 --> 00:03:34.660
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: And so what that means

00:03:34.660 --> 00:03:37.190
is, first of all Twilight is a terrible, terrible
thing.

00:03:37.190 --> 00:03:41.910
It’s basically like a stalker positioned
as an object of desire to convince young girls

00:03:41.910 --> 00:03:45.760
that they want to live this sort of life that’s
very, very destructive to their egos and their

00:03:45.760 --> 00:03:46.760
self-esteem.

00:03:46.760 --> 00:03:50.130
And it’s horrible for America and the world,
so I tried to do what I can.

00:03:50.130 --> 00:03:55.020
So opening weekends I go to the theater, I
sit in the back, and I live tweet the movie

00:03:55.020 --> 00:03:56.020
but with hate.

00:03:56.020 --> 00:03:57.190
So I call it live hate tweeting.

00:03:57.190 --> 00:03:58.480
And it’s amazing.

00:03:58.480 --> 00:04:00.239
I’ve convinced several people not to see
it.

00:04:00.239 --> 00:04:02.220
It’s been worth that investment of my time.

00:04:02.220 --> 00:04:04.129
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: I kinda feel like that

00:04:04.129 --> 00:04:07.530
teacher that wants to reach one student, you
know if you could just change one life.

00:04:07.530 --> 00:04:12.209
Uh, so if I could just convince one person
not to spend fifteen dollars on garbage, then

00:04:12.209 --> 00:04:15.180
I’ve done my job as a citizen.

00:04:15.180 --> 00:04:16.190
So that’s pretty cool.

00:04:16.190 --> 00:04:19.329
And then I’ve written this book and that’s
what we’re here to talk mostly about.

00:04:19.329 --> 00:04:20.769
Uh, the book is called How to Be Black.

00:04:20.769 --> 00:04:26.750
I have a very simple marketing message, if
you don’t buy the book, you’re a racist.

00:04:26.750 --> 00:04:29.180
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: And that’s just true,

00:04:29.180 --> 00:04:32.570
it’s not like a thing, it’s not a hook,
it’s not a scam.

00:04:32.570 --> 00:04:34.039
And it works, it works.

00:04:34.039 --> 00:04:38.110
We actually found out, uh, after the first
week, that we made the New York Times best

00:04:38.110 --> 00:04:39.110
seller list.

00:04:39.110 --> 00:04:40.270
So guilt works ladies and gentlemen.

00:04:40.270 --> 00:04:42.190
[Cheering]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: I highly recommend

00:04:42.190 --> 00:04:43.190
it.

00:04:43.190 --> 00:04:45.540
You guys should try it in your, in your Google
products.

00:04:45.540 --> 00:04:48.949
And those of you at home, your products as
well.

00:04:48.949 --> 00:04:53.940
So before I keep going forward I want to go
back a little bit and then tell you not just

00:04:53.940 --> 00:04:58.210
what I’ve been up to, but where I’ve come
from, and I’ll go back a couple generations.

00:04:58.210 --> 00:05:05.190
This is an image of my great grandfather,
Benjamin Lonesome, born in 1870 in Caroline

00:05:05.190 --> 00:05:10.750
County, Virginia, born a slave, taught himself
to read, as the family story goes, and moved

00:05:10.750 --> 00:05:11.750
to Washington, D.C.

00:05:11.750 --> 00:05:17.380
Now some of you are thinking, “Born a slave
after the emancipation proclamation?”

00:05:17.380 --> 00:05:19.200
Government doesn’t always work ladies and
gentlemen.

00:05:19.200 --> 00:05:20.250
Government doesn’t always work.

00:05:20.250 --> 00:05:21.830
Decrees are not always adhered to.

00:05:21.830 --> 00:05:26.280
But, he moved to D.C. and he worked for the
city and he lived to be quite old actually,

00:05:26.280 --> 00:05:28.100
he had two daughters.

00:05:28.100 --> 00:05:34.440
One of whom was Lorraine Martin, who I didn’t
find out until 2005, that she was the first

00:05:34.440 --> 00:05:36.970
black employee in the US Supreme Court building.

00:05:36.970 --> 00:05:39.250
And we found all these clips in our mom’s
stuff.

00:05:39.250 --> 00:05:42.139
Our mom had passed away, so we’re going
through trying to figure out what to keep

00:05:42.139 --> 00:05:43.139
and what not to keep.

00:05:43.139 --> 00:05:46.570
We’re like, “Hey, we have this great family
history we did not know about.”

00:05:46.570 --> 00:05:48.710
Now, our grandmother was a very proud woman.

00:05:48.710 --> 00:05:50.660
She’s pretty well educated for the time.

00:05:50.660 --> 00:05:55.280
She traveled a lot more than was normal for
black people of the era.

00:05:55.280 --> 00:06:00.410
She did not necessarily spend a lot of her
own time, uh, raising her own daughter.

00:06:00.410 --> 00:06:02.490
She had this really adorable daughter.

00:06:02.490 --> 00:06:04.300
This is my mother, Arnita Thurston.

00:06:04.300 --> 00:06:06.680
You can see where my cuteness comes from.

00:06:06.680 --> 00:06:09.449
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: So she sent, our grandmother

00:06:09.449 --> 00:06:14.430
sent our mother off to Boarding School at
age 8.

00:06:14.430 --> 00:06:17.050
In a little town called Cornwells Heights,
Pennsylvania.

00:06:17.050 --> 00:06:22.520
At the time it was a rural farming community,
now it’s a thriving suburb of Philadelphia.

00:06:22.520 --> 00:06:26.940
And my mother had some trouble adjusting to
this environment, little black girl away from

00:06:26.940 --> 00:06:32.050
her home in the city cast off into an all-black
Catholic boarding school.

00:06:32.050 --> 00:06:34.470
Kareem Abdul Jabbar went to this boarding
school.

00:06:34.470 --> 00:06:37.150
He was not Kareem Abdul Jabbar at the time
he went there.

00:06:37.150 --> 00:06:40.830
I’m not sure they would have admitted him,
uh, if he had been.

00:06:40.830 --> 00:06:42.160
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: But my mother had some

00:06:42.160 --> 00:06:43.250
tough times at this school.

00:06:43.250 --> 00:06:47.500
So tough that she wrote letters back to her
mother and I want to share just one of them

00:06:47.500 --> 00:06:49.080
that my sister and I found.

00:06:49.080 --> 00:06:54.660
This is letter, in the 8-year-old handwriting,
sent from a daughter to her mother, “Dear

00:06:54.660 --> 00:06:59.340
Mother, I am having fun but I do not like
it here.”

00:06:59.340 --> 00:07:03.830
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: “I am mad at you.

00:07:03.830 --> 00:07:05.300
Please send me some cookies.”

00:07:05.300 --> 00:07:07.690
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: Very important.

00:07:07.690 --> 00:07:10.419
“And a Sparkle Plenty doll.”

00:07:10.419 --> 00:07:15.310
Sparkle Plenty was this character, very, very
popular back in the 40s and 50s.

00:07:15.310 --> 00:07:18.180
“Please, uh, they can have dolls here.

00:07:18.180 --> 00:07:22.199
Please send it because I do not have anything
to play with.

00:07:22.199 --> 00:07:24.830
Yours Truly, Arnita.

00:07:24.830 --> 00:07:29.820
So it’s an adorable, sad letter from a daughter
to her mother.

00:07:29.820 --> 00:07:32.650
But I want you to focus on the lower left
corner of this letter.

00:07:32.650 --> 00:07:39.860
This very neat handwriting, very different
font, uh, different color scheme, says “over.”

00:07:39.860 --> 00:07:45.760
When you flip the letter over you see this
note, which says, “If your little girl is

00:07:45.760 --> 00:07:52.540
dissatisfied, we’d be glad to have her bed
for children who are anxious to come.”

00:07:52.540 --> 00:07:58.389
Signed, “Sister” Which is sort of like
the NSA wiretapping of, I guess, 1948.

00:07:58.389 --> 00:08:00.330
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: You gotta protect the

00:08:00.330 --> 00:08:02.770
nation from little black girls that want dolls
and cookies.

00:08:02.770 --> 00:08:06.229
It’s very much a threat to the nation.

00:08:06.229 --> 00:08:08.729
So my mother did not stay long at that school.

00:08:08.729 --> 00:08:13.960
But she did stay within the confines of what
was expected of a modern Negro woman.

00:08:13.960 --> 00:08:19.380
This is her as a teenager wearing a dress
below the knees, carrying a basket, probably

00:08:19.380 --> 00:08:21.230
full of happy feelings about America.

00:08:21.230 --> 00:08:22.810
I’m sure what was in that basket.

00:08:22.810 --> 00:08:28.490
She worked at her high school newspaper, but
before long her social network changed and

00:08:28.490 --> 00:08:31.250
she started hanging out with people that looked
like this.

00:08:31.250 --> 00:08:33.450
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: This is a dude name

00:08:33.450 --> 00:08:34.450
El Dorado.

00:08:34.450 --> 00:08:35.450
[Laughter]
[Murmurs]

00:08:35.450 --> 00:08:36.950
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: Like the car.

00:08:36.950 --> 00:08:39.390
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: And there are many

00:08:39.390 --> 00:08:41.890
people in this world who, uh, who think they’re
cool.

00:08:41.890 --> 00:08:46.590
Some people watching this right now think
you’re cool and know people who are cool.

00:08:46.590 --> 00:08:47.750
You’re not.

00:08:47.750 --> 00:08:49.050
You’re friends aren’t.

00:08:49.050 --> 00:08:54.190
This dude, El Dorado, is the last cool person
to ever have existed.

00:08:54.190 --> 00:08:55.790
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: Look at the shoes,

00:08:55.790 --> 00:08:59.529
look at the phone; look at the typewriter,
the pants, the hair, everything about this

00:08:59.529 --> 00:09:01.150
picture is cool.

00:09:01.150 --> 00:09:05.290
Cool is now a historic relic thanks to the
high bar El Dorado set.

00:09:05.290 --> 00:09:06.560
But my mom didn’t stop there.

00:09:06.560 --> 00:09:07.779
She started getting political.

00:09:07.779 --> 00:09:08.779
She was joining rallies.

00:09:08.779 --> 00:09:10.160
She was out in the streets.

00:09:10.160 --> 00:09:15.250
This is African Liberation Day Parade outside
of Malcolm X Park in Washington, D.C., headed

00:09:15.250 --> 00:09:17.110
south on 16th street northwest.

00:09:17.110 --> 00:09:19.670
And right in the thick of it is my mom.

00:09:19.670 --> 00:09:21.200
[Laughs]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: Cause the revolution

00:09:21.200 --> 00:09:22.899
may not be televised but it could be photographed.

00:09:22.899 --> 00:09:24.440
You want your hair done up right.

00:09:24.440 --> 00:09:26.830
You want the eyes focused on the camera.

00:09:26.830 --> 00:09:30.290
[Pause]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: Now, when I was born,

00:09:30.290 --> 00:09:34.391
my mother did not leave these politics behind,
she very much infused them with me.

00:09:34.391 --> 00:09:37.920
A lot of kids had little books when they were,
you know, you had cartoons.

00:09:37.920 --> 00:09:40.080
You had See Spot Run and stuff like that.

00:09:40.080 --> 00:09:41.080
I didn’t have that.

00:09:41.080 --> 00:09:43.390
This was my first book, pretty much.

00:09:43.390 --> 00:09:45.670
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: Called This is Apartheid.

00:09:45.670 --> 00:09:47.790
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: I had another book

00:09:47.790 --> 00:09:51.260
called Africa is Not a Country, it’s a Continent.

00:09:51.260 --> 00:09:55.260
And when you are raised with this, like stark
black and white photos of Apartheid.

00:09:55.260 --> 00:09:57.110
[Laughs]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: It maybe has a little

00:09:57.110 --> 00:10:01.180
effect on you as a young person whose mind
is being molded.

00:10:01.180 --> 00:10:03.839
Now, outside of our house is a very different
picture.

00:10:03.839 --> 00:10:09.970
This was a constant view from our front window
of Newton Street in the Columbia Heights neighborhood

00:10:09.970 --> 00:10:11.649
of Washington, D.C.

00:10:11.649 --> 00:10:14.760
Lots of drugs deals and other stuff going
on, very much like the Wire.

00:10:14.760 --> 00:10:16.930
When the Wire came out I was traumatized and
excited.

00:10:16.930 --> 00:10:19.860
I was like, “I love this show, but I have
flashbacks.”

00:10:19.860 --> 00:10:24.279
'Cause my neighborhood was just like the Wire,
you know, we had the drug dealing, the police

00:10:24.279 --> 00:10:27.290
corruption, we had everything the Wire had,
right?

00:10:27.290 --> 00:10:32.700
Except for universal critical acclaim, uh,
and the undying love of white people who saw

00:10:32.700 --> 00:10:33.700
it.

00:10:33.700 --> 00:10:34.700
Our neighborhood did not have that.

00:10:34.700 --> 00:10:35.700
[Laughs]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: But otherwise it was

00:10:35.700 --> 00:10:37.029
very similar to the Wire.

00:10:37.029 --> 00:10:42.459
So my mom help navigate me and my sister through
this environment and we had this very proud

00:10:42.459 --> 00:10:45.540
moment at my college graduation from Harvard.

00:10:45.540 --> 00:10:50.170
And she gave me this big hug and said, “We
did it!” and my sister is so proud of capturing

00:10:50.170 --> 00:10:53.560
this moment, she’s like, “I’m the best
photographer ever.”

00:10:53.560 --> 00:10:59.589
And so that’s kind of where I have come
from and it’s the foundation of what this

00:10:59.589 --> 00:11:05.010
book is and kind of this conversation I wanna
start off with you guys here today.

00:11:05.010 --> 00:11:09.500
So, let me talk about how the book was born,
first of all.

00:11:09.500 --> 00:11:11.410
And there’s, there’s a lot of the personal
stuff in there.

00:11:11.410 --> 00:11:14.340
But there’s also like a tech story too and
I think it’s pretty interesting to be talking

00:11:14.340 --> 00:11:16.580
about that at Google.

00:11:16.580 --> 00:11:21.490
The book was born on Twitter via a hash tag.

00:11:21.490 --> 00:11:27.720
And essentially I was shopping for wine and
I didn’t know how to buy wine.

00:11:27.720 --> 00:11:31.970
There’s all this history of wine flavors
and the air of frankincense or whatever, I

00:11:31.970 --> 00:11:33.330
don’t know how to do all that stuff.

00:11:33.330 --> 00:11:37.910
And I was also not interested in learning,
so, I just wanted a bottle of wine.

00:11:37.910 --> 00:11:42.839
I went to the shop and I saw this brand of
wine called Negroamaro.

00:11:42.839 --> 00:11:47.870
N-E-G-R, we’re gonna have to riot now aren’t
we?

00:11:47.870 --> 00:11:49.521
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: We’re just, this

00:11:49.521 --> 00:11:50.860
is the black history month.

00:11:50.860 --> 00:11:55.690
A black man can’t speak at Google without
some white guy talking loudly over top of

00:11:55.690 --> 00:11:56.690
him.

00:11:56.690 --> 00:11:58.800
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: This is ridiculous.

00:11:58.800 --> 00:12:00.860
I got 29 days man, c’mon.

00:12:00.860 --> 00:12:03.149
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: Interrupt me in March

00:12:03.149 --> 00:12:04.890
and I will not complain.

00:12:04.890 --> 00:12:07.339
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: Anyway, I was talking

00:12:07.339 --> 00:12:10.700
about my ignorant wine purchasing decisions.

00:12:10.700 --> 00:12:16.070
[Laughs]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: So I saw this brand

00:12:16.070 --> 00:12:20.090
of wine called Negroamaro, I was like, that
spoke to me, “Negro wine!

00:12:20.090 --> 00:12:21.090
This is perfect.

00:12:21.090 --> 00:12:23.180
That’s why I’m gonna buy it.”

00:12:23.180 --> 00:12:27.970
So I posted to Twitter, and I was trying to
antagonize my friend, Elon James White who’s

00:12:27.970 --> 00:12:29.060
a great comedian.

00:12:29.060 --> 00:12:32.470
He does a web series called This Week in Blackness
and Blackin’ It Up.

00:12:32.470 --> 00:12:36.640
And I said, “This weekend I picked my red
wine because it was called Negroamaro, that’s

00:12:36.640 --> 00:12:37.660
how black I am.

00:12:37.660 --> 00:12:39.209
Elon James, how black are you?”

00:12:39.209 --> 00:12:40.990
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: I was just sort of

00:12:40.990 --> 00:12:43.230
picking a fight playing a little joke back
and forth.

00:12:43.230 --> 00:12:47.710
And then he responded, “I see the subtle
racial implication of Thunder Cat.

00:12:47.710 --> 00:12:50.880
Panther was black, shirtless and Lionel’s
driver.

00:12:50.880 --> 00:12:52.530
How black are you?”

00:12:52.530 --> 00:12:56.959
And so we went back and forth, volleying and
hundreds of other people weighed in and threw

00:12:56.959 --> 00:12:59.269
in their observations on how black are you.

00:12:59.269 --> 00:13:04.930
Then the audience for this was a member of
the Harper Collins team, a woman named Debbie

00:13:04.930 --> 00:13:05.930
Stier.

00:13:05.930 --> 00:13:09.460
And she brought me in and we had a nice conversation
and said, “You should write a book.

00:13:09.460 --> 00:13:12.410
Why don’t you write a book called how black
are you?”

00:13:12.410 --> 00:13:14.600
And I was like, “Why don’t I not do that?”

00:13:14.600 --> 00:13:16.530
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: “That is a terrible

00:13:16.530 --> 00:13:17.530
idea!”

00:13:17.530 --> 00:13:18.779
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: Cause it was one thing

00:13:18.779 --> 00:13:23.050
to have that conversation and that tension
and that battle between two people who know

00:13:23.050 --> 00:13:27.170
each other, two people who are comedians and
we have assumed the best intentions.

00:13:27.170 --> 00:13:28.660
I don’t wanna hit America with that.

00:13:28.660 --> 00:13:30.190
I don’t trust America with that.

00:13:30.190 --> 00:13:32.610
I just had visions of watermelons dancing
in my head.

00:13:32.610 --> 00:13:34.010
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: People are like, “How

00:13:34.010 --> 00:13:35.010
black are you?

00:13:35.010 --> 00:13:36.410
I drink grape soda all the time!”

00:13:36.410 --> 00:13:38.070
And I’m like, ‘No, no, no.’

00:13:38.070 --> 00:13:42.250
America’s not ready for how black are you
at the Wal Mart bookshelf, like we can’t

00:13:42.250 --> 00:13:43.250
do that just yet.

00:13:43.250 --> 00:13:45.510
We have some ways to go.

00:13:45.510 --> 00:13:47.000
But they said, “What about how to be black?”

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:48.850
And I was like, “Yes!

00:13:48.850 --> 00:13:50.340
That is ridiculous.

00:13:50.340 --> 00:13:53.170
You can’t answer that, thus I want to try.”

00:13:53.170 --> 00:13:59.110
And, uh, and be satirical about it, which
gives me some latitude and just have fun with

00:13:59.110 --> 00:14:00.340
the impossible.

00:14:00.340 --> 00:14:04.940
So the book was gonna be a series of “How
To” chapters.

00:14:04.940 --> 00:14:10.790
The first one was “How to speak for all
black people” um, and “How to be the black

00:14:10.790 --> 00:14:12.410
friend” “How to be the black employee.”

00:14:12.410 --> 00:14:14.400
Which, clearly you guys might have an interest
in.

00:14:14.400 --> 00:14:15.400
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: “Tell us how to do

00:14:15.400 --> 00:14:16.400
it!

00:14:16.400 --> 00:14:17.400
Tell us how to do it!”

00:14:17.400 --> 00:14:18.400
Its coming, its coming.

00:14:18.400 --> 00:14:19.860
Just buy the book.

00:14:19.860 --> 00:14:24.761
Uh, but, there was another part of, sort of
the product development of the book, that

00:14:24.761 --> 00:14:27.460
I want to share what was not expected.

00:14:27.460 --> 00:14:29.720
And I want to talk about the role that e-mail
played.

00:14:29.720 --> 00:14:33.930
So I had this vision of, I’m gonna write
just a straight up satire set of chapters

00:14:33.930 --> 00:14:35.830
on “How to.”

00:14:35.830 --> 00:14:37.630
Separate from this, I operate an e-mail list.

00:14:37.630 --> 00:14:38.980
I’ve been doing it for years.

00:14:38.980 --> 00:14:40.110
I thought e-mail was dead.

00:14:40.110 --> 00:14:43.180
I was like, “Ah, Facebook is here and Google
plus is here and Twitter is here.

00:14:43.180 --> 00:14:44.910
Nobody reads e-mail anymore.”

00:14:44.910 --> 00:14:49.920
But because we live in such a fast paced,
sort of, status update-isphere, I wanted to

00:14:49.920 --> 00:14:53.079
have a deeper relationship with the people
who wanted a connection with me.

00:14:53.079 --> 00:14:56.260
So the e-mail became a more of a behind the
scenes.

00:14:56.260 --> 00:15:00.320
And rather than just promoting shows, and
doing a few one liner jokes, is that every

00:15:00.320 --> 00:15:05.130
e-mail I send, I’m gonna have a true personal
story as a part of it.

00:15:05.130 --> 00:15:09.130
So the same summer that I was doing the initial
rounds of writing this book, separate from

00:15:09.130 --> 00:15:12.120
that I was sharing these personal stories
with my e-mail list.

00:15:12.120 --> 00:15:17.990
And one story I shared, which really struck
a nerve, I told the story of my father’s

00:15:17.990 --> 00:15:21.060
murder and what my memory of him was.

00:15:21.060 --> 00:15:23.730
And I really only had six memories of this
dude.

00:15:23.730 --> 00:15:27.410
He died when I was very young; he didn’t
live with us even for the time when he was

00:15:27.410 --> 00:15:28.430
alive.

00:15:28.430 --> 00:15:33.230
And I sent this out, I was on a bus, I was
on a Bolt bus to Boston, like a $15 bus, on

00:15:33.230 --> 00:15:37.010
the Wi-Fi, banged this out in a couple hours,
sent it off.

00:15:37.010 --> 00:15:41.389
And the flood of responses that came back
from my subscribers was overwhelming.

00:15:41.389 --> 00:15:44.930
And one of those subscribers was my editor
at the time, Debbie Stier.

00:15:44.930 --> 00:15:47.300
And she wrote, “This needs to go into the
book!”

00:15:47.300 --> 00:15:52.449
And she’s like, “All these stories are
just too rich; you can’t not use them.

00:15:52.449 --> 00:15:55.670
And I know it’s not part of the original
vision, but maybe we need to rethink what

00:15:55.670 --> 00:15:57.089
this book should be.”

00:15:57.089 --> 00:15:58.360
So she, “Just write those.

00:15:58.360 --> 00:16:00.420
Don’t worry about the super hilarious stuff.

00:16:00.420 --> 00:16:01.910
This is, and this was still funny.

00:16:01.910 --> 00:16:07.050
Even the piece I wrote about my father’s
murder by gunshot was still darkly hilarious,

00:16:07.050 --> 00:16:09.230
uh, if you’re open to that.

00:16:09.230 --> 00:16:12.250
Which I was, I’ve been doing this for a
while.

00:16:12.250 --> 00:16:18.110
So I reconceived of what the book should be
and then personal memoir actually became the

00:16:18.110 --> 00:16:19.950
heart of it.

00:16:19.950 --> 00:16:26.230
So let’s talk about what’s inside, between
these pages, between these bytes, in the electronic

00:16:26.230 --> 00:16:27.230
version.

00:16:27.230 --> 00:16:28.389
First off, it is my life.

00:16:28.389 --> 00:16:34.100
It is the story of a young black dude who
has an eccentric black background, and not

00:16:34.100 --> 00:16:36.740
just black background, obviously there’s
more to me then black.

00:16:36.740 --> 00:16:41.570
But there is that story that people have heard
a lot of, that inner city, single mother,

00:16:41.570 --> 00:16:43.170
gun violence and drugs thing.

00:16:43.170 --> 00:16:44.170
That’s one.

00:16:44.170 --> 00:16:49.839
There’s the Afrocentric rearing the fact
that I have a Nigerian name and I’m not

00:16:49.839 --> 00:16:50.839
Nigerian.

00:16:50.839 --> 00:16:54.230
[laughter] I remember I had a friend that
was Nigerian when I was growing up and I called

00:16:54.230 --> 00:16:58.740
him on the phone, and his Nigerian father
answered and he’s like, “Hello?

00:16:58.740 --> 00:16:59.740
Who’s calling?”

00:16:59.740 --> 00:17:01.579
And I was like, “Oh, sir this is Baratunde.”

00:17:01.579 --> 00:17:02.860
I might have been like 12 years old.

00:17:02.860 --> 00:17:04.959
“Where did you get that name?”

00:17:04.959 --> 00:17:07.389
Its like, how do you even answer that first
of all?

00:17:07.389 --> 00:17:10.209
I got it, oh I don’t know, the secret stash
of names that are mine.

00:17:10.209 --> 00:17:11.679
I got it from my parents.

00:17:11.679 --> 00:17:13.659
And he’s like, “Well do you even know
what it means?”

00:17:13.659 --> 00:17:14.699
And I was like, “Yeah.”

00:17:14.699 --> 00:17:17.199
And this is why I was really proud, cause
I had this super Afrocentric mother.

00:17:17.199 --> 00:17:19.499
She’s like, “You have to understand all
this stuff.”

00:17:19.499 --> 00:17:23.429
And I was like, “Literally it means Grandfather
returns or father returns.

00:17:23.429 --> 00:17:27.139
Or one that was chosen” And he’s like,
“No!

00:17:27.139 --> 00:17:31.429
No. it means grandfather returns or one who
was chosen.”

00:17:31.429 --> 00:17:34.960
It’s like, I just said that.

00:17:34.960 --> 00:17:39.480
Just said, you know how adults can be with
respect to children, they can’t hear you.

00:17:39.480 --> 00:17:41.129
Then he went on a rampage.

00:17:41.129 --> 00:17:44.899
He was like, “This is the problem with you
African Americans.

00:17:44.899 --> 00:17:46.460
You have no history.

00:17:46.460 --> 00:17:47.460
No culture.

00:17:47.460 --> 00:17:48.460
No roots.

00:17:48.460 --> 00:17:52.729
You think you can wear a dashiki, steal an
African name and become African.

00:17:52.729 --> 00:17:54.179
You cannot.”

00:17:54.179 --> 00:17:58.970
I was like, “Dude, I just learned how to
add last week, like slow down.”

00:17:58.970 --> 00:18:01.509
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: Why are you hating

00:18:01.509 --> 00:18:02.509
on me?

00:18:02.509 --> 00:18:03.509
I’m a baby.

00:18:03.509 --> 00:18:05.190
[Laughs]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: Pick a fight with someone

00:18:05.190 --> 00:18:06.570
your own ignorance.

00:18:06.570 --> 00:18:09.989
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: So the book has stories

00:18:09.989 --> 00:18:10.989
like that.

00:18:10.989 --> 00:18:15.249
It also has a lot of the “How to’s”
There’s how to, how to be the next black

00:18:15.249 --> 00:18:17.030
president, one of my favorite chapters.

00:18:17.030 --> 00:18:22.509
A lot of restrictions around president Obama,
especially his relationship to black America

00:18:22.509 --> 00:18:23.509
and black people.

00:18:23.509 --> 00:18:26.749
Certain issues he can’t talk about because
they think he’s gonna like, reinstitute

00:18:26.749 --> 00:18:27.749
white slavery.

00:18:27.749 --> 00:18:29.139
Yes, I said reinstitute.

00:18:29.139 --> 00:18:31.970
We tried it once; it lasted for like a day.

00:18:31.970 --> 00:18:33.830
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: And so there’s, you

00:18:33.830 --> 00:18:35.980
know, some, some guidelines for the next black
president.

00:18:35.980 --> 00:18:40.330
And also the theory being that the second
black president really is the first black

00:18:40.330 --> 00:18:44.169
president, cause the next time around America’s
doing it super intentional, like we know what

00:18:44.169 --> 00:18:45.169
we’re gonna get.

00:18:45.169 --> 00:18:47.200
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: So number 2 is actually

00:18:47.200 --> 00:18:49.309
number 1.

00:18:49.309 --> 00:18:51.609
And then I, uh, so it created a panel.

00:18:51.609 --> 00:18:53.320
And I didn’t wanna interview too many people.

00:18:53.320 --> 00:18:56.260
So I picked seven folks, I call them the black
panel.

00:18:56.260 --> 00:18:58.960
People who I thought were doing blackness
well.

00:18:58.960 --> 00:19:01.500
And differently than what we commonly see.

00:19:01.500 --> 00:19:03.440
And so here’s who’s on that panel.

00:19:03.440 --> 00:19:07.070
There is three black women, starting with
Demali Ayo.

00:19:07.070 --> 00:19:09.529
Demali is a performance artist and a writer.

00:19:09.529 --> 00:19:13.169
She wrote a book called Obamastan: Land without
Racism.

00:19:13.169 --> 00:19:18.129
I came across her in about 2003 when I was
just early in my own stand-up career and I

00:19:18.129 --> 00:19:21.649
found this website called rentanegro dot com.

00:19:21.649 --> 00:19:24.500
I was like, “What in the world is that?”

00:19:24.500 --> 00:19:29.581
It was just hilarious, satirical product offering
where she’s like, “Look white people have

00:19:29.581 --> 00:19:32.580
a lot of questions of their black friends.

00:19:32.580 --> 00:19:37.950
We need to monetize this and set up some sort
of leasing system.”

00:19:37.950 --> 00:19:39.850
So she had rentanegro dot com, she had prices.

00:19:39.850 --> 00:19:42.419
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: She had all this stuff.

00:19:42.419 --> 00:19:47.070
She was inspired by this other dude, Keith
Obadike , who tried to auction off his blackness

00:19:47.070 --> 00:19:48.070
on E-Bay.

00:19:48.070 --> 00:19:51.490
And, uh, and sold it for not enough money.

00:19:51.490 --> 00:19:53.860
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: So Demali, she’s

00:19:53.860 --> 00:19:55.169
gotta be in the book, gotta be in the book.

00:19:55.169 --> 00:19:58.109
It turns out that we went to the same high
school with the same friends.

00:19:58.109 --> 00:20:00.909
I didn’t even know that until we started
talking.

00:20:00.909 --> 00:20:05.510
Cheryl Contee, she is the co-founder with
me of Jack and Jill Politics.

00:20:05.510 --> 00:20:09.130
Based in the Bay area, runs a social media
strategy firm.

00:20:09.130 --> 00:20:12.340
Um, Jacquetta Szathmari, she was someone I
did not know at all.

00:20:12.340 --> 00:20:14.249
A friend connected me to her.

00:20:14.249 --> 00:20:19.450
A black woman who lives up in Riverside up
in the Bronx, Libertarian, and grew up in

00:20:19.450 --> 00:20:20.809
the eastern shore of Maryland.

00:20:20.809 --> 00:20:21.899
She was like my rural vector.

00:20:21.899 --> 00:20:24.880
I was like, “Okay, let’s not keep it too
city focused.”

00:20:24.880 --> 00:20:28.059
And she had a bunch of great stories to share.

00:20:28.059 --> 00:20:29.159
And then I had three black men.

00:20:29.159 --> 00:20:32.230
I had Kamau Bell who’s a Bay area comedian.

00:20:32.230 --> 00:20:34.409
[Applause]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: Yeah, can we clap for

00:20:34.409 --> 00:20:35.409
them?

00:20:35.409 --> 00:20:36.480
Kamau, he, uh, I like this dude.

00:20:36.480 --> 00:20:39.239
I remembered hearing about him cause people
kept saying like, “I was like the Kamau

00:20:39.239 --> 00:20:40.239
of the east.”

00:20:40.239 --> 00:20:41.899
Or he was the Baratunde of the west.

00:20:41.899 --> 00:20:43.240
Why can’t black dudes just be each other?

00:20:43.240 --> 00:20:44.330
Like why do you have to?

00:20:44.330 --> 00:20:46.730
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: But um, he has a great

00:20:46.730 --> 00:20:52.099
one man show called The W. Kamau Bell Curve,
which is a playoff of the Bell Curve book

00:20:52.099 --> 00:20:53.820
by Charles Murray.

00:20:53.820 --> 00:20:58.389
Who incidentally, Charles Murray has a new
book out about whiteness and I love that he

00:20:58.389 --> 00:21:00.179
launched it during black history month.

00:21:00.179 --> 00:21:01.179
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: Just couldn’t let

00:21:01.179 --> 00:21:02.779
us have it, right?

00:21:02.779 --> 00:21:07.059
Anyway, Kamau’s show, the subtitles is ending
racism in about an hour.

00:21:07.059 --> 00:21:11.119
And he puts his money where his mouth is,
if you show up with a friend of a different

00:21:11.119 --> 00:21:13.039
race, you get in for half price.

00:21:13.039 --> 00:21:14.149
So that’s kind of nice.

00:21:14.149 --> 00:21:15.259
That’s kind of nice.

00:21:15.259 --> 00:21:19.309
Elon James White, who I mentioned earlier,
Brooklyn based comedian, This Week in Blackness

00:21:19.309 --> 00:21:21.409
and Blacking it Up, web shows.

00:21:21.409 --> 00:21:26.190
Derrick Ashong, who is a musician primarily,
but also a speaker and a TV host.

00:21:26.190 --> 00:21:30.029
He has a band called Soulfege, he works for
Al Jazeera English.

00:21:30.029 --> 00:21:34.919
And Derrick, for me, also represented a bit
of the diaspora because he was born in Ghana.

00:21:34.919 --> 00:21:39.210
He was raised in all around the Middle East
in Qatar, Saudi Arabia.

00:21:39.210 --> 00:21:43.639
And he spend his teen years and after in the
east coast, in the Philadelphia, New Jersey

00:21:43.639 --> 00:21:44.679
area.

00:21:44.679 --> 00:21:47.640
So he was kind of that global brother.

00:21:47.640 --> 00:21:51.279
And then I had one white guy, uh, on the panel
because I didn’t want to get hit with charges

00:21:51.279 --> 00:21:52.830
of reverse racism.

00:21:52.830 --> 00:21:55.999
And I wanted a control group cause this is
a science project as well.

00:21:55.999 --> 00:21:57.409
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: And so I picked the

00:21:57.409 --> 00:22:01.629
whitest guy I could find, who’s Christian
Lander, who is the author of Stuff White People

00:22:01.629 --> 00:22:02.629
Like.

00:22:02.629 --> 00:22:04.249
And help create that amazing set.

00:22:04.249 --> 00:22:07.850
And I really wanted the idea, like the idea
of a white comedian commenting on how to be

00:22:07.850 --> 00:22:11.010
black was just too good to not try.

00:22:11.010 --> 00:22:12.029
And he came through.

00:22:12.029 --> 00:22:17.470
So what I wanna share now is, uh, some of
the questions that I asked these people.

00:22:17.470 --> 00:22:20.249
I asked them, “When did you first realize
you were black?”

00:22:20.249 --> 00:22:22.360
“How black are you?”

00:22:22.360 --> 00:22:25.130
“Did you ever wish you weren’t black?”

00:22:25.130 --> 00:22:26.429
“Can you swim?”

00:22:26.429 --> 00:22:30.090
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: A very important question.

00:22:30.090 --> 00:22:34.720
“How’s that post-racial thing workin out
for you?” and, “What do you wish for the

00:22:34.720 --> 00:22:38.450
future of black people and race in general
in America?”

00:22:38.450 --> 00:22:40.240
So seven people, seven questions.

00:22:40.240 --> 00:22:43.970
It’s a nice grid of 49 clips.

00:22:43.970 --> 00:22:49.159
And then what I did was I video recorded them
and also use a zoom audio mic to get some

00:22:49.159 --> 00:22:50.190
good audio.

00:22:50.190 --> 00:22:53.309
So here is a sample of one of those clips.

00:22:53.309 --> 00:22:57.710
[Pause]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: Oh, I should press

00:22:57.710 --> 00:22:59.210
play.

00:22:59.210 --> 00:23:17.350
This is a compilation around one of the answers.

00:23:17.350 --> 00:23:28.419
[Music plays]

00:23:28.419 --> 00:24:21.789
&gt;&gt; Female #1: So, I came home and I remember
I couldn’t really move past the entrance

00:24:21.789 --> 00:24:30.989
of the house.

00:24:30.989 --> 00:25:12.029
And I need to talk about the fact that this
little girl said that I was black when I,

00:25:12.029 --> 00:25:13.309
in fact, found myself to be beige.

00:25:13.309 --> 00:25:14.309
[Music plays]

00:25:14.309 --> 00:25:19.080
&gt;&gt; Male #1: I was playing doctor with a bunch
of kids and, uh, when this one girl, it was

00:25:19.080 --> 00:25:21.719
her turn to kiss me and she didn’t.

00:25:21.719 --> 00:25:24.074
And she sort of ran away laughing, the kids
ran away laughing.

00:25:24.074 --> 00:25:25.074
And the thing I realized at that point is
that I was black and they were all white because

00:25:25.074 --> 00:25:26.074
this was a small private school in Boston.

00:25:26.074 --> 00:25:27.074
And that was the first time I remember feeling
like black was somehow separate from the norm,

00:25:27.074 --> 00:25:28.074
you know.

00:25:28.074 --> 00:25:29.074
I think I knew I was black before then because,
as I say in my show, my mom would not have

00:25:29.074 --> 00:25:30.074
not let me know that I was black.

00:25:30.074 --> 00:25:31.074
[Laughs]
&gt;&gt; Male #1: There would have been no way that

00:25:31.074 --> 00:25:32.074
she would have let that information slip.

00:25:32.074 --> 00:25:33.074
“It’s cold outside take a jacket and you’re
black”.

00:25:33.074 --> 00:25:34.074
[Laughter]
[Music plays]

00:25:34.074 --> 00:25:35.074
&gt;&gt; Male #2: I was born in Africa, so everybody’s
black.

00:25:35.074 --> 00:25:36.074
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt; Male #2: So, we don’t really think about

00:25:36.074 --> 00:25:37.074
it like that.

00:25:37.074 --> 00:25:38.074
I mean here it’s like “Is he black?

00:25:38.074 --> 00:25:39.074
Is he white?”

00:25:39.074 --> 00:25:40.074
In Africa, like, you don’t ask.

00:25:40.074 --> 00:25:41.074
The assumption is that you’re black.

00:25:41.074 --> 00:25:42.074
Therefore, what becomes more important is
other things.

00:25:42.074 --> 00:25:43.074
What your name is, where you come from, what
language do you speak, what’s your culture,

00:25:43.074 --> 00:25:44.074
what’s your tribe etcetera.

00:25:44.074 --> 00:25:45.074
So I knew I was black.

00:25:45.074 --> 00:25:46.074
When I was eight, I moved to the Middle East.

00:25:46.074 --> 00:25:47.074
I think the Middle East is the first time
