me about this.”

00:27:42.820 --> 00:27:45.539
I got an e-mail from a friend of mine during
this process.

00:27:45.539 --> 00:27:49.830
His name is Anand Giridharadas, he’s a New
York Times columnist, written a book called

00:27:49.830 --> 00:27:50.909
India Calling.

00:27:50.909 --> 00:27:52.899
He’s become a very good friend.

00:27:52.899 --> 00:27:57.889
And he said, “I have an amazing idea for
you as a publicity stunt, create a public

00:27:57.889 --> 00:28:00.730
writing viewing for your final day of writing
the book.”

00:28:00.730 --> 00:28:05.259
He’s in this screen sharing service called
Join dot Me.

00:28:05.259 --> 00:28:07.529
You can share your screen with the world.

00:28:07.529 --> 00:28:08.529
And so I did that.

00:28:08.529 --> 00:28:14.070
I actually, when he wrote, I wrote him back
immediately, a really long e-mail explaining

00:28:14.070 --> 00:28:17.210
why this is a terrible idea and no author
should ever do this.

00:28:17.210 --> 00:28:18.440
[Laughs]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: But as I wrote those

00:28:18.440 --> 00:28:21.929
words I convinced myself otherwise and decided
to give it a shot.

00:28:21.929 --> 00:28:23.739
And so I called it My Live Writing Exercise.

00:28:23.739 --> 00:28:28.410
And I was remembering a friend of mine who
does the live painting, Marc Scheff, and he

00:28:28.410 --> 00:28:32.789
allows you to see him actually paint, digitally,
using a Wacom Tablet.

00:28:32.789 --> 00:28:35.980
And, uh, I’ve seen stuff like that with
construction.

00:28:35.980 --> 00:28:38.489
But never with words, I hadn’t seen someone
do that before.

00:28:38.489 --> 00:28:41.759
So, when people came, this is the screen that
they would see.

00:28:41.759 --> 00:28:44.219
It had a little billboard explaining what
was going on.

00:28:44.219 --> 00:28:49.080
You were watching @Baratunde write How to
Be Black keep the hash tag going.

00:28:49.080 --> 00:28:51.299
Please don’t like, I’m not gonna be chatting
with you.

00:28:51.299 --> 00:28:53.519
People were trying to take control of my machine.

00:28:53.519 --> 00:28:54.659
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: Because you’re gonna

00:28:54.659 --> 00:28:55.659
have that happen.

00:28:55.659 --> 00:28:56.659
And like, “I wanna help you!”

00:28:56.659 --> 00:28:57.659
I’m like, “No!

00:28:57.659 --> 00:28:58.659
No!

00:28:58.659 --> 00:28:59.659
This is still me writing.

00:28:59.659 --> 00:29:00.659
You get to watch.

00:29:00.659 --> 00:29:01.659
Right?

00:29:01.659 --> 00:29:02.659
You get to watch.”

00:29:02.659 --> 00:29:06.419
So they started chatting with each other as
