00:41:25.730 --> 00:41:30.599
And I’m wondering how your experiences at
a black student Harvard might have informed

00:41:30.599 --> 00:41:33.859
some of your later stand-up and your book
and some of the things you talk about.

00:41:33.859 --> 00:41:37.880
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: Yes, so I have, I have
a chapter in the book called Black, “Being

00:41:37.880 --> 00:41:39.130
Black at Harvard.”

00:41:39.130 --> 00:41:41.450
I had good preparation for the Harvard environment.

00:41:41.450 --> 00:41:45.130
I went to boot camp, also known as private
white high school.

00:41:45.130 --> 00:41:46.829
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: And, I went to Sidwell

00:41:46.829 --> 00:41:50.670
Friend School, where the Obama daughters go,
where Chelsea Clinton was two years behind

00:41:50.670 --> 00:41:51.670
me.

00:41:51.670 --> 00:41:53.910
And that was my big cultural adjustment.

00:41:53.910 --> 00:41:57.910
I’d been in D.C. public schools before then
and my neighborhood was all black and Latino.

00:41:57.910 --> 00:42:01.599
There were two white kids in my class in grade
school.

00:42:01.599 --> 00:42:03.490
One was William, one was Willamina.

00:42:03.490 --> 00:42:07.150
So as far as I knew all white people had the
same name.

00:42:07.150 --> 00:42:08.809
So Sidwell was culture shock.

00:42:08.809 --> 00:42:10.500
I had Ebonics when I showed up.

00:42:10.500 --> 00:42:11.550
I axed people questions.

00:42:11.550 --> 00:42:13.319
It’s a very long road.

00:42:13.319 --> 00:42:14.680
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: I’ve gotten through

00:42:14.680 --> 00:42:16.040
it now, I’ve gotten through it.

00:42:16.040 --> 00:42:17.660
I got treatment.

00:42:17.660 --> 00:42:23.170
And, so Harvard for me was very liberating
because I’d gone through the whole process

00:42:23.170 --> 00:42:25.880
of being the minority in the educational institution.

00:42:25.880 --> 00:42:28.799
Harvard certainly keeps changing in the types
of black people that go there, too.

00:42:28.799 --> 00:42:34.029
At the time that I was there, I think half
or to just slightly majority were not American

00:42:34.029 --> 00:42:38.559
native black, but were immigrants from some
other place, from the Caribbean from across

00:42:38.559 --> 00:42:39.559
the Diaspora.

00:42:39.559 --> 00:42:41.519
That changes things, that changes thing culturally.

00:42:41.519 --> 00:42:45.400
We also have people who much, many more people
over the history of Harvard who’ve had a

00:42:45.400 --> 00:42:48.859
private school background, mixing with those
who have public school background, mixing

00:42:48.859 --> 00:42:50.950
with those from the Diasporic background.

00:42:50.950 --> 00:42:57.009
So I did not, I was one of those dudes that
like hung out with the blackity black crowd

00:42:57.009 --> 00:42:58.359
and like sat at the black table.

00:42:58.359 --> 00:43:02.869
But also I, like, I talked to white people
because they were there and had knowledge

00:43:02.869 --> 00:43:07.569
in their brains that I wanted, and friendship
in their hearts.

00:43:07.569 --> 00:43:11.039
So I think I had a pretty idealized experience
because I was so very prepared.

00:43:11.039 --> 00:43:13.840
I don’t know that everyone had that experience.

00:43:13.840 --> 00:43:16.059
You know everyone’s got their own college
experience, too.

00:43:16.059 --> 00:43:22.119
I would like to think that the mix of the
type of black people in each Harvard class

00:43:22.119 --> 00:43:26.090
over time contributes to a little bit less
of the black card pulling.

00:43:26.090 --> 00:43:31.010
Except for mine, which I hope to monetize
and get all those people to invest using the

00:43:31.010 --> 00:43:32.010
black card.

00:43:32.010 --> 00:43:33.230
Thank you.

