because my cousin, you know, looks like a

00:53:45.400 --> 00:53:46.400
white girl.

00:53:46.400 --> 00:53:52.350
So I just wanted to know, is there one thing
that makes somebody black, or is it hard to

00:53:52.350 --> 00:53:53.350
define?

00:53:53.350 --> 00:53:57.050
&gt;&gt;Baratunde Thurston: Oh, what makes someone
black?

00:53:57.050 --> 00:54:01.150
Black parents help, at least one.

00:54:01.150 --> 00:54:07.480
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: I would never say that

00:54:07.480 --> 00:54:14.170
it’s some checklist of cultural markers
and knowledge cause that’s, that’s a falsely

00:54:14.170 --> 00:54:16.430
limiting thing.

00:54:16.430 --> 00:54:22.130
But I also, we also know that scientifically
speaking, there’s no such thing as race,

00:54:22.130 --> 00:54:26.690
if you wanna go to the genetic thing and try
to define it that way.

00:54:26.690 --> 00:54:29.369
It’s in between those two falsehoods.

00:54:29.369 --> 00:54:36.780
There’s a truth of blackness which is some
history, which is some phenotypical set of

00:54:36.780 --> 00:54:38.869
things, some, but not exclusively.

00:54:38.869 --> 00:54:40.440
You have very white looking black people.

00:54:40.440 --> 00:54:42.519
You have very black looking white peo- no.

00:54:42.519 --> 00:54:44.589
You don’t have any black looking white people.

00:54:44.589 --> 00:54:50.819
But, um, yeah the idea, I also would be very
careful of this idea that anyone can just

00:54:50.819 --> 00:54:52.890
declare themselves to be black.

00:54:52.890 --> 00:54:58.200
I remember there was a rap group, maybe in
the early 90s, Young Black Teenagers.

00:54:58.200 --> 00:55:01.299
And they’re like, “Blackness isn’t a
race, it’s a state of mind, man.”

00:55:01.299 --> 00:55:03.450
It’s like, no, it’s not.

00:55:03.450 --> 00:55:07.779
You can’t just write yourself in as a candidate
for blackness.

00:55:07.779 --> 00:55:10.731
And that’s a little, that level of flexibility
is a little dangerous.

00:55:10.731 --> 00:55:16.960
But we’re in some magical times where those
cultural markers are open to so many people.

00:55:16.960 --> 00:55:20.040
When you put the popularity of entertainment
especially Hip Hop.

00:55:20.040 --> 00:55:24.890
Hip Hop’s such a global culture started
very black but has grown far beyond that.

00:55:24.890 --> 00:55:26.980
Being in rap doesn’t make you black.

00:55:26.980 --> 00:55:28.609
It makes you really into Hip Hop.

00:55:28.609 --> 00:55:31.769
But it doesn’t change your race.

00:55:31.769 --> 00:55:33.249
This book doesn’t make anyone black.

00:55:33.249 --> 00:55:36.839
It can make you look blacker, I think, by
sharing some of a black experience that you

00:55:36.839 --> 00:55:39.869
may not have heard about and having some fun
with it.

00:55:39.869 --> 00:55:44.680
So I’m gonna ramble through that answer
and say there’s no, there’s no measure

00:55:44.680 --> 00:55:47.530
of black to be in and out.

00:55:47.530 --> 00:55:49.750
You kinda know it, if you are.

00:55:49.750 --> 00:55:54.309
And if you’re not, then that’s cool too.

00:55:54.309 --> 00:55:56.720
[Pause]
&gt;&gt;Baratunde Thurston: You might be the last

00:55:56.720 --> 00:55:57.720
one.

00:55:57.720 --> 00:55:59.640
Yeah, you are the last one.

00:55:59.640 --> 00:56:00.640
Congrats.

00:56:00.640 --> 00:56:01.640
&gt;&gt; Female #9: I am the last one?

00:56:01.640 --> 00:56:02.640
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: Make it amazing.

00:56:02.640 --> 00:56:03.640
&gt;&gt;Female #9: Oh, gosh the pressure.

00:56:03.640 --> 00:56:04.640
I don’t know if it is but I’ll see.

00:56:04.640 --> 00:56:08.980
I’m Mary and, um, I was raised, I grew up
in a predominately white area.

00:56:08.980 --> 00:56:09.980
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: Yeah.

00:56:09.980 --> 00:56:10.980
&gt;&gt;Female #9: There was about five black families.

00:56:10.980 --> 00:56:12.619
&gt;&gt;Baratunde Thurston: Out of how many?

00:56:12.619 --> 00:56:14.520
&gt;&gt;Female #9: Oh, I don’t know, like 30,000.

00:56:14.520 --> 00:56:15.730
You know, central coast.

00:56:15.730 --> 00:56:19.369
San Luis Obispo County, I don’t know if
you guys know where that is.

00:56:19.369 --> 00:56:20.369
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: Okay.

00:56:20.369 --> 00:56:25.950
&gt;&gt; Female #9: I grew up in a beach town and
I don’t know where to swim.

00:56:25.950 --> 00:56:26.950
[Laughter]

00:56:26.950 --> 00:56:29.579
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: Just a moment of silence.

00:56:29.579 --> 00:56:30.670
&gt;&gt; Female #9: I try, I try, I try.

00:56:30.670 --> 00:56:33.230
But anyway, my parents always taught me to
speak to other black people.

00:56:33.230 --> 00:56:36.550
So if I see other black people, maybe it’s
because it was predominately white.

00:56:36.550 --> 00:56:37.550
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: Yeah.

00:56:37.550 --> 00:56:38.550
&gt;&gt; Female #9: You speak to each other.

00:56:38.550 --> 00:56:39.770
They say “Hi.”

00:56:39.770 --> 00:56:43.740
And my white friends always find it funny
because they don’t walk around saying hi

00:56:43.740 --> 00:56:44.799
to each other.

00:56:44.799 --> 00:56:48.250
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Female #9: And I think the younger generation,

00:56:48.250 --> 00:56:52.789
cause I’m older, so who said they were the
oldest in the room?

00:56:52.789 --> 00:56:53.789
I bet I’m older.

00:56:53.789 --> 00:56:54.789
But anyway.

00:56:54.789 --> 00:56:55.789
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: She left, I think.

00:56:55.789 --> 00:56:56.789
It was nap time.

00:56:56.789 --> 00:56:57.789
I'm kidding.

00:56:57.789 --> 00:56:58.789
&gt;&gt; Female #9: She was too old.

00:56:58.789 --> 00:56:59.789
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt; Female #9: So the younger people don’t

00:56:59.789 --> 00:57:00.789
do it.

00:57:00.789 --> 00:57:03.210
So sometimes I’ll say hi and there like
well ya know?

00:57:03.210 --> 00:57:08.109
I was just wondering did you grow up doing
that, or were you raised to do that?

00:57:08.109 --> 00:57:09.109
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: Yeah, that’s.

00:57:09.109 --> 00:57:11.579
Great question, great closing question.

00:57:11.579 --> 00:57:15.230
I did grow up acknowledging other black people,
I still acknowledge other black people.

00:57:15.230 --> 00:57:21.600
I think the folks who don’t do that, I think
it’s very regional, in my experience.

00:57:21.600 --> 00:57:28.711
When I moved from D.C. to Boston I encountered
a level of coldness in the city that I’ve

00:57:28.711 --> 00:57:29.711
never experienced.

00:57:29.711 --> 00:57:33.670
I was always told that New York was a very
rough and cold town and Boston is much more

00:57:33.670 --> 00:57:36.369
distant, you know, much more insider or outsider.

00:57:36.369 --> 00:57:37.900
And not just among black people, with all
people.

00:57:37.900 --> 00:57:39.520
People don’t say hi on the street in Boston.

00:57:39.520 --> 00:57:40.809
Like, “What do you, what do you want?

00:57:40.809 --> 00:57:43.589
“ Like, “Just a human connection.”

00:57:43.589 --> 00:57:44.589
[Laughter]

00:57:44.589 --> 00:57:45.589
&gt;&gt;Baratunde Thurston: “You came to the wrong
city!

00:57:45.589 --> 00:57:46.759
Get out!

00:57:46.759 --> 00:57:47.759
Go back south!”

00:57:47.759 --> 00:57:49.999
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Baratunde Thurston: So I, I actually write

00:57:49.999 --> 00:57:52.569
about this in “How to Be a Black Friend.”

00:57:52.569 --> 00:57:57.910
I say one of the keys on the premise of this
being, you’re a black person, who is friends,

00:57:57.910 --> 00:58:02.579
one of, if not only minority in the group
of non-black people especially white people,

00:58:02.579 --> 00:58:05.930
you have an obligation to acknowledge other
black people.

00:58:05.930 --> 00:58:08.329
Because you’re on a mission, you’re basically
an undercover agent.

00:58:08.329 --> 00:58:11.839
And you’re delivering messages, and communication,
you’re learning, you’re preventing a race

00:58:11.839 --> 00:58:16.009
war by telling your white friends not to touch
your hair or use the “N” word.

00:58:16.009 --> 00:58:21.349
But if you don’t acknowledge other black
people it raises suspicions about your commitment

00:58:21.349 --> 00:58:23.230
to the cause.

00:58:23.230 --> 00:58:28.309
So I was always to, like, at least a head
nod, just a little something.

00:58:28.309 --> 00:58:31.369
Maybe, maybe one of these, you know if you’re
really.

00:58:31.369 --> 00:58:33.329
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Baratunde Thurston: If it’s the day, like,

00:58:33.329 --> 00:58:37.089
if you’ve reached the moment when it’s
like it’s on, you got the memo.

00:58:37.089 --> 00:58:39.839
It's like, “Let’s do it!”

00:58:39.839 --> 00:58:40.839
[Laughter]

00:58:40.839 --> 00:58:41.950
&gt;&gt;Baratunde Thurston: Or maybe just a smile.

00:58:41.950 --> 00:58:44.039
I just needed the subtle eye contact.

00:58:44.039 --> 00:58:49.880
So I have not experienced much of, black people
were comfortable being black people but not

00:58:49.880 --> 00:58:51.160
acknowledging other black people.

00:58:51.160 --> 00:58:54.390
I think I have seen that among some that are
like, “I’m kind of undercover here.

00:58:54.390 --> 00:58:57.430
I don’t want people to know that I know
that I’m black.”

00:58:57.430 --> 00:59:00.140
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Baratunde Thurston: So keep doing it.

00:59:00.140 --> 00:59:05.799
We’ll try to train the younger generation
to stay on message and on mission.

00:59:05.799 --> 00:59:10.180
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Baratunde Thurston: I am gonna end my talk

00:59:10.180 --> 00:59:11.180
on this.

00:59:11.180 --> 00:59:13.200
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt; Baratunde Thurston: Thank you Google, thank

00:59:13.200 --> 00:59:15.510
you black people, thank you all people.

00:59:15.510 --> 00:59:16.170
I’m Baratunde.

